<TITLE> Ahmadinejad tells foreign powers to quit region </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BAGHDAD, March 3 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Iranian President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad used a visit to Baghdad on Monday to tell the United States to pull out of Iraq, saying its presence there had brought only destruction and division. "Iraq throughout history has been against foreigners and occupiers," Ahmadinejad said at a news conference on the second day of his state visit to Iraq, the first by an Iranian leader since the two neighbours fought an eight-year war in the 1980s. "We believe the power that came over the seas ... These powers should leave this region and hand over the affairs to the people and governments in the region," he said in translated remarks. Ahmadinejad has repeatedly called on the United States to pull out its more than 150,000 troops in Iraq, saying it was to blame for violence that has killed tens of thousands. The U.S.-led invasion that toppled Saddam Hussein in 2003 unleashed sectarian tensions between majority Shi'ites and minority Sunni Arabs that pushed Iraq close to civil war. Washington accuses Tehran of fuelling violence with its support for Shi'ite militias in Iraq, a charge Tehran denies. The United States is also at loggerheads with Iran over its nuclear programme. "Foreign states should not interfere in the affairs of states. Peoples and governments of these states are capable of running their own affairs without the presence of foreigners," Ahmadinejad said. "People have not seen anything from the foreign presence in this region but more destruction and division." The Iranian president has also sought to counter U.S. efforts to isolate Tehran over its nuclear programme, which Washington says is for nuclear weapons, by trying to improve ties with Arab states in the region. The UN Security Council is expected to vote on Monday on a third round of sanctions against Iran over its nuclear programme, which Iran says is for peaceful purposes but the United States says is for nuclear ar
